ball|Football]]}}\n{{MedalCountry|{{fb|ESP}}}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA World Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 South Africa]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[UEFA European Championship]]}}\n{{Medal|W|[[UEFA Euro 2012|2012 Poland-Ukraine]]|}}\n{{MedalCompetition|[[FIFA Confederations Cup]]}}\n{{Medal|3rd|[[FIFA Confederations Cup 2009|2009 South Africa]]|}}\n{{Medal|RU|[[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup|2013 Brazil]]|}}\n}}\n'''Gerard Piqu\u00e9 Bernabeu''' ({{IPA-ca|\u0292\u0259\u02c8\u027ea\u027et pi\u02c8ke \u03b2\u0259\u027en\u0259\u02c8\u03b2ew|lang}}, {{IPA-es|\u025f\u029de\u02c8\u027ea\u027e pi\u02c8ke \u03b2e\u027ena\u02c8\u03b2eu|lang}}; born 2 February 1987) is a Spanish professional [[Association football|footballer]] who plays as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre-back]] for [[FC Barcelona|Barcelona]].  Piqu\u00e9 is considered to be one of the best defenders in the world.<ref name=\"Ten of the Best Defenders in the World\">{{cite web|url=http://worldsoccer.about.com/od/internationals/tp/worldcupdefenders.htm|title=Ten of the Best Defenders in the World|publisher=World Soccer|accessdate=17 September 2014}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9 joined [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]] academy in 2004, where he remained for four years. He returned to Bar\u00e7a under [[Pep Guardiola]]'s leadership and helped the club win [[Treble (association football)|trebles]] in 2008\u201309 and 2014\u201315. He is one of four players to have won the [[UEFA Champions League]] two years in a row with different teams, the others being [[Marcel Desailly]], [[Paulo Sousa]] and [[Samuel Eto'o]].<ref>{{cite web|first=Roger |last=Boguny\u00e0 |title=Three titles and personal records |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada08-09/05/n090528105280.html |archive-url=https://archive.today/20120731180228/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada08-09/05/n090528105280.html |url-status=dead |archive-date=31 July 2012 |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=28 May 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9 has also represented [[Spain national football team|Spain]] 102 times, making his debut on 11 February 2009. He played an integral role in the Spain teams that won the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]] and [[UEFA Euro 2012]].\n\n==Club career==\n===Early career===\nBorn in [[Barcelona]], Catalonia,<ref name=FCBprofile/> Piqu\u00e9 started his career in [[FC Barcelona]]'s youth teams as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]], but before he signed his first professional contract with the club, he decided to join [[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]. The [[Premier League]] side did not pay a fee for Piqu\u00e9 as he was too young to have a professional contract.\n\n===Manchester United===\nPiqu\u00e9 made his debut for Manchester United in October 2004, as a centre back, a 67th minute replacement for [[John O'Shea]] in a 3\u20130 [[Football League Cup|League Cup]] victory at [[Crewe Alexandra F.C.|Crewe Alexandra]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Crewe 0\u20133 Man Utd |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/league_cup/3947037.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=26 October 2004 |accessdate=27 May 2008}}</ref> He made his full debut in January 2005 in a 0\u20130 [[FA Cup]] draw with [[Exeter City F.C.|Exeter City]]. Pique made his [[2005\u201306 FA Premier League|Premier League]] debut on 15 October 2005, again as a substitute for O'Shea, in a 3\u20131 win over [[Sunderland F.C.|Sunderland]]. His first league start came on 29 March 2006 against [[West Ham United F.C.|West Ham United]] at [[Old Trafford]], playing at [[Defender (association football)#Full-back|right back]], as [[Gary Neville]] was unavailable through injury.<ref>{{cite news |title=Man Utd 1\u20130 West Ham |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/eng_prem/4842340.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=29 March 2006 |accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nHis performances, most notably in [[Manchester United F.C. Reserves and Academy#Reserves|the reserve team]], earned him a new contract, which he signed in February 2005, to run until the summer of 2009. On 4 August 2006, however, [[La Liga]] side [[Real Zaragoza]] secured Piqu\u00e9 on a season-long loan. The conditions of the loan involved Piqu\u00e9 having to feature in at least 20 games for the Aragonese club,<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.ontheminute.com/news/news.php?news=2521 |title=Zaragoza's Piqu\u00e9: My future is with Man Utd |publisher=OnTheMinute.com |accessdate=30 January 2007}}</ref> which he did, as he made 22 first team appearances in a successful spell, alongside Argentine [[Gabriel Milito]], either as a centre back or a defensive midfielder.\n\nOn 5 May 2007, it was announced that Piqu\u00e9 would be staying at Old Trafford for the following season. [[Alex Ferguson|Sir Alex Ferguson]] had intended to assess Piqu\u00e9's form at [[La Romareda]] on 6 May, prior to a meeting where the two parties would discuss Piqu\u00e9's future prospects with the club. However, Ferguson was unable to attend on account of airline difficulties.<ref>{{cite web |first=Ben |last=Hibbs |title=Piqu\u00e9 set for OT return |url=http://www.manutd.com/en/News-And-Features/Football-News/2007/May/Pique-set-for-OT-return.aspx |publisher=Manchester United F.C. |date=4 May 2007 |accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9's return to Old Trafford saw him make nine league appearances during the [[Premier League 2007\u201308|2007\u201308 season]]. In his first start in the [[UEFA Champions League]], a 4\u20130 home win against [[FC Dynamo Kyiv|Dynamo Kyiv]] on 7 November 2007, Piqu\u00e9 scored the first of Manchester United's four goals in that match.<ref>{{cite news |first=Phil |last=McNulty |title=Man Utd 4\u20130 Dynamo Kiev |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/7076590.stm |work=BBC Sport |date=7 November 2007 |accessdate=3 May 2010}}</ref> In doing so, he became the 450th player to score at least one goal for the club.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.stretfordend.co.uk/goalscorers/overall.html |title=All Goalscorers in all Competitive Matches |accessdate=8 November 2007 |date=November 2007 |work=The Website of Dreams |publisher=StretfordEnd.co.uk |page=5}}</ref> His second goal for the club also came in the Champions League, in an away match to [[A.S. Roma|Roma]] on 12 December 2007.<ref>{{cite news |first=Ian |last=Herbert |title=Roma 1 Manchester United 1: Piqu\u00e9's joy on pitch marred by violence off it |url=https://www.independent.co.uk/sport/football/european/roma-1-manchester-united-1-piques-joy-on-pitch-marred-by-violence-off-it-764878.html |newspaper=The Independent |date=13 December 2007 |accessdate=25 June 2010}}</ref>\n\n===Return to Barcelona===\n[[File:Gerard Pique.jpg|thumb|Piqu\u00e9 during the 2008 [[Joan Gamper Trophy]]]]\nOn 27 May 2008, Piqu\u00e9 signed a four-year contract with Barcelona, with a \u20ac5&nbsp;million buy-out clause.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada07-08/05/n080527104344.html |title=Piqu\u00e9 comes back home |publisher=FC Barcelona |accessdate=25 June 2010 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=http://archive.wikiwix.com/cache/20100627200942/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/web/english/noticies/futbol/temporada07-08/05/n080527104344.html |archivedate=27 June 2010 }}</ref> Barcelona paid a \u00a35&nbsp;million fee for the player.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sid |last=Lowe |title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 is back at Camp Nou, the man with Barcelona in his DNA |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/24/gerard-pique-barcelona-champions-league |newspaper=The Guardian |date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=30 November 2010}}</ref> He expressed his joy at re-signing with his boyhood club, although he admitted he had enjoyed his spell at Manchester United:\n{{bquote|I am very happy to be back, I didn't think I would be here again but this is very good for me. Manchester United is a great club and I enjoyed winning things. To play with world class players has helped me and now I want to continue this at Bar\u00e7a.}}\n\nPiqu\u00e9's first goal for Barcelona came in the club's 2\u20135 [[2008\u201309 UEFA Champions League group stage|Champions League group stage]] win at [[Sporting CP]] on 26 November 2008.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://espnfc.com/uk/en/gamecast/254714/gamecast.html?soccernet=true&cc=5739|title=Sporting Lisbon 2 \u2013 5 Barcelona|publisher=ESPN FC |date=26 November 2008|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/competitions/champions-league/3528746/Jose-Mourinhos-Inter-Milan-progress-despite-defeat-to-Panathinaikos-Football.html|title=Jose Mourinho's Inter Milan progress despite defeat to Panathinaikos |newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=26 November 2008|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> His first domestic goal for the club followed two months later, on 29 January 2009, in a [[2008\u201309 Copa del Rey|Copa del Rey]] match against local rivals [[RCD Espanyol|Espanyol]]. The goal, which came from a [[corner kick]] in the 57th minute, turned out to be the game winner in a 3\u20132 victory for Barcelona.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=261375&cc=5901 |title=Barcelona 3 \u2013 2 Espanyol |accessdate=2 July 2009|date=29 January 2009 |publisher=ESPN FC}}</ref><ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/4391354/Barcelona-into-Copa-del-Rey-semis.html|title=Barcelona into Copa del Rey semis|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=29 January 2009|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> On 2 May 2009, Piqu\u00e9 scored Barcelona's sixth goal in a 2\u20136 ''[[El Cl\u00e1sico]]'' win against [[Real Madrid C.F.|Real Madrid]] at the [[Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium]], which saw him produce a passionate [[goal celebration]] where he grabbed his Barcelona jersey.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.marca.com/en/football/barcelona/2017/04/24/58fe5ed8ca47413f548b461c.html|title=Real Madrid-Barcelona: Celebrations in enemy territory|newspaper=[[Marca (newspaper)|Marca]]|date=24 April 2017|accessdate=16 October 2018}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/card/real-madrid-fc-barcelona-2-6|title=REAL MADRID \u2013 FC BARCELONA 2\u20136|date=2 May 2009|accessdate=10 August 2013|publisher=FC Barcelona|archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20140228091954/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/card/real-madrid-fc-barcelona-2-6|archive-date=28 February 2014|url-status=dead|df=dmy-all}}</ref>\n\nOn 13 May 2009, he picked up the first trophy of his Barcelona career as he helped his club to a 4\u20131 victory over [[Athletic Bilbao]] in the [[2009 Copa del Rey Final|Copa del Rey Final]].<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/5321324/Barcelona-defeat-Athletic-Bilbao-to-win-Copa-del-Rey.html|title=Barcelona defeat Athletic Bilbao to win Copa del Rey|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=14 May 2009|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> Three days later, Barcelona clinched the [[2008\u201309 La Liga|league title]] after Real Madrid lost 3\u20132 to [[Villarreal CF|Villarreal]], with two games left in the season.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.telegraph.co.uk/sport/football/european/5336603/Real-Madrid-loss-hands-La-Liga-title-to-Barcelona.html|title=Real Madrid loss hands La Liga title to Barcelona|newspaper=The Daily Telegraph|date=16 May 2009|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>\n\n[[File:Bar\u00e7a - Napoli - 20140806 - Echauffement - Gerard Piqu\u00e9 (edited).jpg|thumb|180px|right|Piqu\u00e9 warming up for Barcelona in August 2014]]\nOn 27 May 2009, Piqu\u00e9 played against his former club Manchester United in the [[2009 UEFA Champions League Final|2009 Champions League Final]], which Barcelona won 2\u20130,<ref>{{cite news|url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/europe/8060878.stm|title=Barcelona 2\u20130 Man Utd |work=BBC Sport|date=27 May 2009|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> completing a historic [[Treble (association football)|treble]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2009/matches/round=15280/match=302813/postmatch/quotes/index.html|title=Guardiola salutes his treble winners|publisher=UEFA|date=28 May 2009|accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref>\n\nOn 19 December 2009, Piqu\u00e9 was in the Barcelona team which beat [[Argentina|Argentine]] club [[Estudiantes de La Plata|Estudiantes]] 2\u20131 in the [[2009 FIFA Club World Cup Final|Club World Cup Final]]. Piqu\u00e9 [[Assist (football)|assisted]] [[Pedro (footballer, born July 1987)|Pedro]]'s 89th minute equalising goal which took the match to [[Overtime (sports)|extra-time]].<ref>{{cite news|url=http://edition.cnn.com/2009/SPORT/football/12/19/football.barcelona.estudiantes.messi/index.html|title=Barcelona add world title to trophy haul|date=19 December 2009|accessdate=10 August 2013|publisher=CNN}}</ref>\n\nOn 26 February 2010, Piqu\u00e9 signed a contract extension to keep him at Barcelona until at least summer 2015.<ref>{{cite news |title=Piqu\u00e9 signs new Barcelona deal |url=http://www.mirrorfootball.co.uk/news/Pique-signs-new-Barca-deal-article336557.html |work=MirrorFootball |publisher=Mirror Group Newspapers |date=26 February 2010 |accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Piqu\u00e9 extends Barcelona contract |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/news/newsid=1455997.html |publisher=UEFA |date=26 February 2010 |accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> On 28 April 2010, Piqu\u00e9 scored in Barcelona's [[2009\u201310 UEFA Champions League|Champions League]] semi-final second leg against [[Inter Milan]], though his side went out 3\u20132 on aggregate.<ref>[http://soccernet.espn.go.com/match?id=290736&league=UEFA.CHAMPIONS&cc=4716 Barcelona 1 \u2013 0 Internazionale] ESPN Soccernet, 28 April 2010</ref>\n\nOn 28 May 2011, Piqu\u00e9 played in his second [[2011 UEFA Champions League Final|Champions League Final]]. Bar\u00e7a defeated Manchester United 3\u20131 at [[Wembley Stadium]] to lift the [[European Champion Clubs' Cup|European Cup]] for the second time in three seasons. On 1 May 2013, Piqu\u00e9 scored an own goal for [[FC Bayern Munich|Bayern Munich]] in [[Camp Nou]], making the score 2\u20130 to Bayern. Later, Bayern went on to win 3\u20130 and 7\u20130 on aggregate.<ref>[http://espnfc.com/news/story/_/id/1431988/gerard-pique-worst-moment-my-barcelona-career?cc=4716] ESPN FC, 1 May 2013</ref>\n\nOn 20 May 2014, Piqu\u00e9 signed a contract extension with Barcelona, keeping him at the club until 2019.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 signs on till 2019 |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/gerard-pique-signs-on-till-2019 |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=20 May 2014 |accessdate=22 May 2014}}</ref>\n\nOn 6 June 2015, Piqu\u00e9 started for Bar\u00e7a in the [[2015 UEFA Champions League Final]], as the club won its fifth European Cup by beating [[Juventus F.C.|Juventus]] at [[Berlin]]'s [[Olympiastadion Berlin|Olympiastadion]].<ref>{{cite web |first=Andrew |last=Haslam |title=Barcelona see off Juventus to claim fifth title |url=http://www.uefa.com/uefachampionsleague/season=2015/matches/round=2000552/match=2015227/postmatch/report/index.html |publisher=UEFA |date=6 June 2015 |accessdate=7 June 2015}}</ref> This made Barcelona the first club in history to win the [[Treble (association football)|treble]] of domestic league, domestic cup and European Cup twice.<ref name=triple>{{cite web |title=Bar\u00e7a make history with second treble! |url=http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/barca-make-history-with-second-treble |publisher=FC Barcelona |date=6 June 2015 |accessdate=7 June 2015 |archive-url=https://web.archive.org/web/20150607120500/http://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/detail/article/barca-make-history-with-second-treble |archive-date=7 June 2015 |url-status=dead |df=dmy-all }}</ref> Piqu\u00e9, [[Lionel Messi]], [[Andr\u00e9s Iniesta]], [[Xavi]], [[Sergio Busquets]], [[Dani Alves]] and Pedro are the only players to have been a part of both treble-winning teams.<ref name=triple/>\n\nOn 18 January 2018, Piqu\u00e9 extended his contract again, this time until 2022.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2017-2018/gerard-pique-renews-with-fc-barcelona-through-to-2022|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 and FC Barcelona renew contract through to 2022|date=18 January 2018|accessdate=18 January 2018|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20181001142512/https://www.fcbarcelona.com/football/first-team/news/2017-2018/gerard-pique-renews-with-fc-barcelona-through-to-2022|archivedate=1 October 2018|publisher=FC Barcelona}}</ref> On 25 August 2019, he played full 90 minutes in a 5-2 win against [[Real Betis]], his 500th game for the club.<ref>{{Cite web|url=https://www.fcbarcelona.com/en/news/1320074/gerard-pique-reaches-500-games-for-fc-barcelona|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 reaches 500 games for FC Barcelona|date=25 August 2019|website=FC Barcelona|language=en|access-date=26 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==International career==\n===Youth teams===\nPiqu\u00e9 was a member of the [[Spain national under-19 football team|Spain under-19 side]] that won the [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Championship]] in Poland.<ref>[http://www.uefa.com/under19/news/newsid=439848.html Mel\u00e9ndez's mind focused on final] UEFA, 27 July 2006</ref> In a [[2006 UEFA European Under-19 Championship#Final|2\u20131 final]] win against [[Scotland national under-19 football team|Scotland]], Piqu\u00e9 put in a strong performance in defence and also contributed in attack, hitting the crossbar with a header and providing the assist for [[Forward (association football)|striker]] [[Alberto Bueno]] to score Spain's second goal.<ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.uefa.com/under19/news/newsid=440340.html |title='This defeat feels like a victory' |website=UEFA.com |date=30 July 2006 }}</ref>\n\nSubsequently, he played in the [[2007 FIFA U-20 World Cup]], starting all six of Spain's matches and scoring a goal in the team's come-from-behind 4\u20132 victory over [[Brazil national under-20 football team|Brazil]] in the round of 16.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spain-Brazil Match Report |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=249409/match=58880/report.html |publisher=FIFA |accessdate=2 April 2008 |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20080214043749/http://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round%3D249409/match%3D58880/report.html |archivedate=14 February 2008 |url-status=dead }}</ref> However, Piqu\u00e9 missed the deciding penalty in the [[Penalty shoot-out (association football)|shoot-out]] against the [[Czech Republic national under-20 football team|Czech Republic]], and Spain were eliminated at the quarter-final stage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Spain \u2013 Czech Republic Match Report |url=https://www.fifa.com/u20worldcup/matches/round=249410/match=58889/report.html |publisher=FIFA |date=14 July 2007 |accessdate=22 June 2013}}</ref>\n\n===Senior side===\n[[File:Spain national football team Euro 2012 final.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Piqu\u00e9 (back row, first from right) lining up before the [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final]]]]\n[[File:Pique&neymar.jpg|thumb|right|220px|Piqu\u00e9 (right) in action for Spain in the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final]]]]\nOn 6 February 2009, Piqu\u00e9 was called up to the [[Spain national football team|senior squad]] for the friendly against [[England national football team|England]] on 11 February.<ref>{{cite news |title=Lista de convocados para el amistoso ante Inglaterra |url=http://www.rfef.es/index.jsp?nodo=39&ID=1120 |publisher=Real Federaci\u00f3n Espa\u00f1ola de F\u00fatbol |date=6 February 2009 |accessdate=6 February 2009 |language=es}}</ref> He played the entire match in a 2\u20130 win, in [[Seville]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Nick |last=Iliev |title=International Friendly: Spain completely outclass England |url=http://www.sofiaecho.com/2009/02/12/673859_international-friendly-spain-completely-outclass-england |newspaper=The Sofia Echo |date=12 February 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010}}</ref> In his second match as an international on 28 March 2009, he was called up as a replacement for injured teammate [[Carles Puyol]] and he scored the only goal in Spain's victory in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup qualification (UEFA)|2010 World Cup qualifier]] against [[Turkey national football team|Turkey]] at the Santiago Bernab\u00e9u Stadium in [[Madrid]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Del Bosque Analyses Spain's Turkey Win |url=http://www.goal.com/en/news/12/spain/2009/03/29/1180402/del-bosque-analyses-spains-turkey-win |publisher=Goal.com |date=29 March 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010}}</ref> Four days later, he also started in [[Istanbul]] in a 2\u20131 win, also in the group stage.<ref>{{cite web |title=Turkey 1\u20132 Spain: Riera earns comeback victory |url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/report?id=236469&cc=5739 |publisher=ESPN FC |date=1 April 2009 |accessdate=25 June 2010}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9 made his tournament debut for Spain at the [[2009 FIFA Confederations Cup]], starting in four of the team's five matches as ''La Roja'' finished in third place.\n\nPiqu\u00e9 was Spain's first-choice centre back playing alongside Puyol at the [[2010 FIFA World Cup|2010 World Cup finals]] in South Africa, starting all seven matches as Spain won the tournament, defeating [[Netherlands national football team|the Netherlands]] 1\u20130 in [[2010 FIFA World Cup Final|the final]].<ref>{{cite news |first=Kevin |last=McCarra |title=World Cup 2010 final: Andr\u00e9s Iniesta finds key for Spain to beat Holland |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2010/jul/11/world-cup-final-holland-spain1 |newspaper=The Guardian |date=11 July 2010 |accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref> Piqu\u00e9's partnership with Puyol saw Spain concede only twice in seven World Cup matches and keep four consecutive [[clean sheets]] in the [[2010 FIFA World Cup knockout stage|knockout stage]]. In Spain's 1\u20130 group stage defeat to [[Switzerland national football team|Switzerland]], just before [[Gelson Fernandes]] scored the only goal of the game, Swiss striker [[Eren Derdiyok]] tumbled over Spain goalkeeper [[Iker Casillas]] and accidentally kicked Piqu\u00e9 in the face, knocking him over and leaving him with a nasty cut beside his right eye.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sam |last=Sheringham |title=Spain 0\u20131 Switzerland |url=http://news.bbc.co.uk/sport1/hi/football/world_cup_2010/matches/match_16 |work=BBC Sport |date=16 June 2010 |accessdate=16 January 2015}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9 played every minute of Spain's [[UEFA Euro 2012]] campaign, partnering [[Sergio Ramos]] in the centre of defence. He successfully converted the team's third penalty in a [[UEFA Euro 2012 knockout stage#Portugal vs Spain|semi-final]] shoot-out win over [[Portugal national football team|Portugal]]. In [[UEFA Euro 2012 Final|the final]], Spain recorded a fifth consecutive clean sheet in a 4\u20130 win over [[Italy national football team|Italy]]. Piqu\u00e9 was one of three Spanish defenders included in [[UEFA]]'s [[UEFA European Championship Team of the Tournament|Team of the Tournament]] as ''La Roja'' conceded only one goal in six matches.\n\nAt the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup]], Piqu\u00e9 was the third of Spain's seven successful takers in a 7\u20136 shootout win over Italy at the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup knockout stage#Spain v Italy|semi-final]] stage. On 30 June 2013, Piqu\u00e9 was [[Ejection (sports)|sent off]] during the [[2013 FIFA Confederations Cup Final|final]] against [[Brazil national football team|Brazil]]. He received a straight [[Penalty card|red card]] in the 68th minute for a violent tackle on recently signed Barcelona teammate [[Neymar]]. The match finished 3\u20130 to Brazil, ending Spain's world record [[Spain national football team results#2010\u20132019|29 match unbeaten run]] in competitive internationals.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bloomberg.com/news/2013-07-01/brazil-caps-confederations-cup-marked-by-protests-with-title.html|title=Brazil Caps Confederations Cup Marked by Protests With Title|date=1 July 2013|accessdate=10 August 2013|publisher=Bloomberg}}</ref>\n\nIn Spain's opening group game of [[UEFA Euro 2016]] on 13 June, Piqu\u00e9 scored his fifth goal for his country, a late [[Header (association football)|header]] in a 1\u20130 victory against the [[Czech Republic national football team|Czech Republic]].<ref>{{cite web |last=Saffer|first=Paul|url=http://www.uefa.com/uefaeuro/season=2016/matches/round=2000448/match=2017883/postmatch/report/index.html|title=Piqu\u00e9 pounces for late Spain win|date=13 June 2016|accessdate=14 June 2016|publisher=UEFA}}</ref>\n\nIn Spain's second group match of the [[2018 FIFA World Cup]] on 20 June, a 1\u20130 win against [[Iran national football team|Iran]], Piqu\u00e9 made his 100th international appearance.<ref>{{cite web |url=http://www.beinsports.com/us/fifa-world-cup/news/diego-costa-guides-spain-past-impressive-iran/907824 |title=Diego Costa Guides Spain Past Impressive Iran |publisher=www.beinsports.com |date=20 June 2018 |accessdate=23 June 2018 }}</ref>\n\nOn 11 August 2018, Piqu\u00e9 announced his retirement from international football.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://en.onefootball.com/%F0%9F%9A%A8-gerard-pique-retires-from-international-football/|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 retires from international football|date=11 August 2018|accessdate=11 August 2018|publisher=One Football}}{{Dead link|date=December 2018 |bot=InternetArchiveBot |fix-attempted=yes }}</ref>\n\nOn 25 March 2019, Pique won his 10th cap for [[Catalonia national football team|Catalonia]] in a friendly match against Venezuela, a few months after he had retired from the Spanish national team and led the team to a 2\u20131 victory.<ref>{{cite news|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/47699030|title=Gerard Pique plays for Catalonia in friendly against Venezuela|date=25 March 2019|work=BBC Sport|accessdate=29 August 2019}}</ref>\n\n==Style of play==\nPiqu\u00e9 is a modern defender, who combines strength with good technique and passing. Due to his height and physical attributes, he is good in the air. Although he is primarily deployed as a [[Defender (association football)#Centre-back|centre back]], he is a tactically versatile player who is capable of playing as a [[Midfielder#Defensive midfielder|defensive midfielder]]; he has also been deployed as a [[Sweeper (association football)|sweeper]] on occasion, showing similarities to [[Germany national football team|German]] legend, [[Franz Beckenbauer]], thus earning the [[sobriquet]] \"Piqu\u00e9nbauer\".<ref>{{cite web |first=Christopher |last=Simpson |title=Gerard Pique Has 'Piquenbauer' Beer Named After Him in Barcelona Tribute |url=http://bleacherreport.com/articles/2650330-gerard-pique-has-piquenbauer-beer-named-after-him-in-barcelona-tribute |website=Bleacher Report |date=6 July 2016 |accessdate=30 April 2017}}</ref> He has also occasionally been known to use his height as an additional attacking threat by advancing into more offensive positions.<ref>{{cite web|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 Bernabeu|url=http://arxiu.fcbarcelona.cat/web/english/futbol/temporada_09-10/plantilla/jugadors/pique.html|accessdate=2 February 2015}}</ref><ref>{{cite news |url=http://www.fourfourtwo.com/news/hierro-piquenbauer-has-strikers-soul#:muJ5K5-LGQpCmA|title=Hierro: 'Piquenbauer' has striker's soul|magazine=FourFourTwo|date=3 May 2010|accessdate=7 January 2016}}</ref>\n\n==Personal life==\nPiqu\u00e9 was raised in a [[Catalan people|Catalan]] family. His father, Joan, is a businessman, and his mother, Montserrat, is the director of a spinal injuries hospital in Barcelona. He has a younger brother, Marc.<ref>{{cite news|url=http://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/noticia.asp?pkid=265037|title=Familia s\u00f3lo hay una|newspaper=El Peri\u00f3dico de Arag\u00f3n|accessdate=15 March 2011|date=5 August 2006|language=Spanish|url-status=dead|archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110710184337/http://www.elperiodicodearagon.com/noticias/noticia.asp?pkid=265037|archivedate=10 July 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://soccernet.espn.go.com/world-cup/player/bio/_/id/45931/gerard-piqu%C3%A9&cc=5901?ver=us|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 \u2013 World Cup 2010 |work=Soccernet |publisher=ESPN|accessdate=15 March 2011}}</ref> His grandfather, Amador Bernabeu, is a former vice-president of Barcelona.<ref>{{cite news |first=Sid |last=Lowe |title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 is back at Camp Nou, the man with Barcelona in his DNA |url=https://www.theguardian.com/football/2009/may/24/gerard-pique-barcelona-champions-league |newspaper=The Guardian |date=25 May 2009 |accessdate=31 May 2009}}</ref> During the [[2017 Catalan independence referendum]], he was seen by many as one of the public faces of the Catalan side of the argument, voting and [[twitter|tweet]]ing his support in [[Catalan language|Catalan]].<ref name=\"bbc-news-1\">{{cite news|last1=West|first1=Andy|title=Catalan referendum: How FC Barcelona found themselves at centre of issue|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/sport/football/41461197|accessdate=2 October 2017|work=BBC Sport |date=1 October 2017}}</ref> He subsequently faced backlash from some Spanish fans for his support of the Catalan independence referendum.<ref name=\"bbc-news-2\">{{cite news|title=Spain fans boo Barcelona's Pique at football training|url=https://www.bbc.co.uk/news/av/world-europe-41482859/spain-fans-boo-barcelona-s-pique-at-football-training|accessdate=3 October 2017|work=BBC News|date=3 October 2017}}</ref>\n\nSince early 2011, Piqu\u00e9 has been in a relationship with Colombian singer [[Shakira]].<ref>{{cite web |title=Piqu\u00e9 confirms Shakira relationship on request from Barcelona coach Guardiola |url=http://www.tribalfootball.com/articles/pique-confirms-shakira-relationship-request-barcelona-coach-guardiola-1434891 |publisher=tribalfootball.com |accessdate=7 February 2011}}</ref> They met when he appeared in the music video for her single \"[[Waka Waka (This Time for Africa)]]\", the official song of the [[2010 FIFA World Cup]].<ref>{{cite news |title=Antonio de la R\u00faa, Shakira's Ex-Boyfriend, Sues Star For $250 Million |url=https://www.huffingtonpost.com/2012/09/06/antonio-de-la-rua-sues-shakira_n_1859324.html |newspaper=The Huffington Post |date=6 September 2012 |accessdate=24 January 2013}}</ref> Piqu\u00e9 and Shakira share the same birthday, but she is ten years his senior. The couple have two children.<ref>{{cite news |url=https://www.mirror.co.uk/3am/celebrity-news/shakira-and-gerard-piques-baby-milan-1586433 |newspaper=Daily Mirror |title=First picture: Shakira and Gerard Piqu\u00e9's two-week-old baby Milan |date=4 February 2013 |accessdate=12 March 2013}}</ref><ref>{{cite web|url=http://www.hellomagazine.com/healthandbeauty/mother-and-baby/2015013023150/shakira-gives-birth-to-second-baby-boy-with-gerard-pique-name-revealed/|title=Shakira baby: The name of the little boy revealed|date=30 January 2015|work=Hellomagazine.com}}</ref>\n\nPiqu\u00e9 was the face of [[Mango (clothing)|Mango]]'s men's line ''HE'' for four consecutive campaign seasons between 2011 and 2012.<ref>{{cite web|url=http://thefashionisto.com/gerard-pique-for-h-e-by-mango-spring-2011-campaign/|title=Gerard Piqu\u00e9 for H.E. by Mango Spring 2011 Campaign|date=24 February 2011|publisher=The Fashionisto|accessdate=29 March 2011}}</ref><ref>{{cite web |first=Michelle |last=Wray |title=Gerard Pique Launches He by Mango Spring/Summer 2011 Collection Pictures |url=http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/features/article_1626314.php/Gerard-Pique-Launches-He-by-Mango-Spring-Summer-2011-Collection-Pictures |publisher=Monsters and Critics |date=15 March 2011 |accessdate=29 March 2011 |url-status=dead |archiveurl=https://web.archive.org/web/20110324152257/http://www.monstersandcritics.com/people/features/article_1626314.php/Gerard-Pique-Launches-He-by-Mango-Spring-Summer-2011-Collection-Pictures |archivedate=24 March 2011 }}</ref><ref>{{cite news |title=Gerard Pique, Mango image for the fourth time |url=http://www.lavanguardia.com/se-lleva/20120723/54328540951/pique-imagen-mango.html |newspaper=La Vanguardia |date=23 July 2012 |accessdate=2 August 2012}}</ref> In 2012, he lent his voice to the Catalan version of ''[[The Pirates! In an Adventure with Scientists!]]'' as the Pirate King.<ref>{{cite web |title=TV3 TN migdia 6_8_2012 Piqu\u00e9 doblatge Pirates |url=https://www.youtube.com/watch?v=IZf-COPsRi0 |publisher=YouTube |accessdate=10 August 2014}}</ref>\n\n===Media and business interests===\nPiqu\u00e9 is the founder and president of Kosmos Holding, a sports and media investment group he started with [[Hiroshi Mikitani]] (founder and chairman of Japanese e-commerce firm [[Rakuten, Inc.]]), Edmund Chu, Nullah Sarker and Mike Evans.<ref>{{cite news |title=Owner of Rakuten supports Gerard Pique in Players Tribune expansion |url=https://www.palco23.com/entorno/el-dueno-de-rakuten-entra-en-una-de-las-empresas-del-holding-de-pique.html |newspaper=Palco 23 |language=Spanish|date=17 April 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> Kosmos has struck a partnership with the [[International Tennis Federation]] for a 25-year, $3 billion partnership that will transform the [[Davis Cup]] and generate substantial revenues for global tennis development.<ref>{{cite news |title=ITF announces plans for transformation of Davis Cup|url=https://www.daviscup.com/news/281842.aspx |newspaper=ITF Tennis |date=26 February 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> In August 2018, U.S. billionaire [[Larry Ellison]] published a public letter stating that he is joining the Kosmos group.<ref>{{cite news |title=American billionaire Larry Ellison backs Indian Wells to host revamped Davis Cup|url=http://www.skysports.com/tennis/news/12110/11464553/american-billionaire-larry-ellison-backs-indian-wells-to-host-revamped-davis-cup |newspaper=Reuters |date=7 August 2018 |accessdate=8 August 2018}}</ref> In December 2018, through his firm Kosmos Holding, Piqu\u00e9 bought Spanish football club [[FC Andorra]]. The club currently competes in the [[Segunda Divisi\u00f3n B]], the third tier in [[Spanish football league system]].<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.football-espana.net/76131/barcelona-defender-gerard-pique-completes-fc-andorra-purchase|title=Barcelona defender Gerard Pique completes FC Andorra purchase|accessdate=31 December 2018|publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a}}</ref><ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.football-espana.net/79500/gerard-piques-fc-andorra-take-final-segunda-b-place|title=Gerard Pique's FC Andorra take final Segunda B place |publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a|accessdate=29 July 2019}}</ref> In July 2019, Piqu\u00e9 took over a majority stake in another Spanish football club - Gimn\u00e0stic Manresa. The take over was also completed using his firm Kosmos Holding.<ref>{{cite web |url=https://football-espana.net/79471/barcelona-defender-gerard-pique-buys-another-football-club|title=Barcelona defender Gerard Pique buys another football club |publisher=Football Espa\u00f1a |accessdate=28 July 2018}}</ref>\n\n===Philanthropy ===\n\nIn response to the [[2019\u201320 coronavirus pandemic]] Pique along with fellow team mates including [[Lionel Messi]] committed to a 70% pay cut in their salaries during the crisis. They further committed to donating towards the salaries of all employees at the club during the state of emergency. <ref>https://www.forbes.com/sites/christinasettimi/2020/03/30/lionel-messis-coronavirus-wage-cut-could-cost-him-50-million/#1d13da445284</ref>\n\n===Tax fraud===\nOn 10 July 2019, Piqu\u00e9 was ordered by a Spanish court to pay \u20ac2.1&nbsp;million to the tax authorities following his conviction for image rights fraud. The defender pretended to hand over his image rights to his Kerad Project company in order to pay less tax from 2008 to 2010.<ref>{{cite web |title=Gerard Pique handed \u20ac2.1 million tax bill |url=https://www.france24.com/en/20190710-gerard-pique-handed-21-million-tax-bill |work=France 24 |date=10 July 2019 |accessdate=10 July 2019 }}</ref>\n\n===Poker tournament results===\nOn 27 August 2019, Piqu\u00e9 took part of EPT Barcelona \u20ac25,000 Single-Day High Roller Event. He finished in second place and won a prize of \u20ac352,950.<ref>{{cite_web|url=https://www.pokernews.com/news/2019/08/fc-barcelona-gerard-pique-ept-barcelona-arturo-vidal-poker-35229.htm|title=FC Barcelona Star Gerard Piqu\u00e9 Wins \u20ac352,950 at EPT Barcelona, Arturo Vidal Cashes \u20ac134,460|accessdate=27 August 2019|publisher=www.pokernews.com}}</ref>\n\n==Career statistics==\n===Club===\n{{updated|match played 7 March 2020}}<ref>{{Soccerbase|id=39937|name=Gerard Pique}}</ref><ref name=SW>{{cite web|url=https://us.soccerway.com/players/gerard-pique-bernabeu/10605/|title=Spain \u2013 G. Pique|publisher=Soccerway|accessdate=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n\n{| class=\"wikitable\" style=\"text-align:center\"\n|+ Appearances and goals by club, season and competition\n|-\n!rowspan=2|Club\n!rowspan=2|Season\n!colspan=3|League\n!colspan=2|National Cup{{efn|Includes [[FA Cup]], [[Copa del Rey]]}}\n!colspan=2|[[EFL Cup|League Cup]]\n!colspan=2|Europe\n!colspan=2|Other\n!colspan=2|Total\n|-\n!Division!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals!!Apps!!Goals\n|-\n|rowspan=5|[[Manchester United F.C.|Manchester United]]\n|[[2004\u201305 Manchester United F.C. season|2004\u201305]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|39937|2004|access-date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n|[[Premier League]]\n|0||0||1||0||1||0||1{{efn|name=UCL|Appearance(s) in [[UEFA Champions League]]}}||0||0||0||3||0\n|-\n|[[2005\u201306 Manchester United F.C. season|2005\u201306]]<ref>{{Soccerbase season|39937|2005|access-date=14 March 2018}}</ref>\n|Premier League\n|3||0||2||0||2||0||0||0||colspan=2|\u2014||7||0\n|-\n|[[2006\u201307 Manchester United F.C. season|2006\u201307]]<ref name=0607season>{{Soccerbase season|39937|200